@jonathanong @skeggse I'd rather not throw 400s unnecessarily, especially by a framework. 

Only the service that utilizes the framework should take care of throwing errors that constitute a 400, which varies with each service built on top of express. 

There are use cases where handling malformed URIs is necessary, such as proxies that take a proxied URI as a part of the path, for example.

@rlidwka I had a similar PR here: https://github.com/visionmedia/express/pull/1735 to fix https://github.com/visionmedia/express/issues/1734.

The issue has some example code. Originally it resulted in a crash though. 

Still, if I do something like `app.get('/*', function(req, res, next){ /* ... */ })`, that does some logic on `req.url`, and navigate to `http://localhost:300/%my_malformed_uri`, I don't want express to get in the way, and respond with either 400 or 500. If I'm not satisfied with the requested URL, I can deal with it on my own however I please.
